## Task A — Precision-Scaling Separation Manifold Boundary Test

**Status: BUILT + VERIFIED** (follow-up `wf_8e25af4d-a4d`). instrument-artifact → **confirmed**;
exact-dominance → **REFUTED**. Two verification outcomes change the build's story: (a) the SR "candidate-real"
caveat is **downgraded — all four fixtures are instrument artifacts**; (b) the named "dominating term" is
**refuted** — at the SR/Schw/PA collapse cells the F1 residual is *exactly zero*, so there is nothing to
dominate. Details below.

**Setup.** Model `C_{p,k} = a_k + u_p·b_k` (Theorem 3 / Task 017c), **path F1**, precision ladder
float32 / float64 / float128 + decimal_50 / decimal_120 anchors; grid `f_max=0.9`, 24 pts/decade down to
`f_min≈1e-12`, forced point at the Sterbenz operand.

**Headline mechanics discovered.** All four fixtures classify the apparent "R²-leaves-1.0" event as
**`degenerate_fit_artifact_not_a_substrate_boundary`** — i.e. the collapse is the linear fit going degenerate
(too few distinct nonzero per-precision residuals to identify a 2-parameter line), not a geometric boundary.
The instrument rule-out splits the fixtures:

| Fixture | Sterbenz | first-dirty-f behaviour | Verdict |
|---|---|---|---|
| pure_algebraic | 0.5 | moves with anchor: decimal_50 `0.7429…` → decimal_120 `0.5572…` | instrument-floor artifact |
| schwarzschild | 4.0 | moves with anchor (same as PA) | instrument-floor artifact |
| cbrt_chain | 0.5 | binary-only ladder | fit-degeneracy artifact |
| **sr** | 1/√2 | anchor-invariant at f≈0.74291… **but** moves 0.74291→0.34492 when **float128** is removed | **instrument artifact** — boundary is the 80-bit float128 noise floor (verified, downgraded) |

**SR downgrade (key verification finding).** SR's decimal-anchor invariance was the wrong test: at the SR
boundary cell only the **float128** tier is nonzero (float32 = float64 = decimal = 0; float128 = 5.42e-20), so
raising the *decimal* anchor cannot move it. Varying the *binary* tier — removing float128 — relocates the
boundary `0.74291…→0.34492…` (stable across decimal_50/120/200/300). SR's "boundary" **is** the 80-bit-extended
float128 tier's noise floor; remove it and it drops to float64's floor. No fixture carries multi-tier substrate
signal at the R²-departure cell.

**Dominating term — REFUTED.** The build reported `dominating_term = eps_pow_squaring_round` (ratio 1.0). The
exact-dominance lens (fractions.Fraction, cross-checked by mpmath at ≥2000-bit) refuted this: at the SR/Schw/PA
collapse cells the **F1 residual is `f1_exact = 0.0` exactly** — the two error terms `eps_pow_squaring_round` and
`eps_root_sqrt_roundtrip` are **equal and opposite**, so `ratio = 1.0` is *parity*, not dominance. The
`dominating_term` label is a `max()`-tie artifact (the dict lists `eps_pow` first). Two further corrections it
surfaced: the build's `−3.105e-17` / operand `7.7794…` belong to **Schwarzschild, not SR** (SR operand is
`0.5070…`); and the Schw and PA collapse records are **byte-identical** (one cell duplicated), so "generality
across fixtures" was not demonstrated. Only cbrt has a genuinely nonzero F1 residual — and there the dominant
term is the **other** one (`eps_root_sqrt_roundtrip`, ratio 6.66). `additive_check_exact = 0` holds but is
trivial (the equal-and-opposite terms cancel). **Caveat for future use:** default-precision mpmath rendered
`−0.0` at 600-bit for these sub-ULP checks — Fraction is the authoritative anchor; mpmath needs ≥2000-bit.

**Burden gates:** (i) exact threshold — **partial** (no single clean threshold); (ii) dominating term —
**REFUTED** (no single term; equal-and-opposite split, F1 residual exactly 0 at the cited cells; per-cell, not
fixture-wide); (iii) not an instrument artifact — **met & verified** (all 4 fixtures are artifacts; SR
downgraded). The top-level classification (degenerate_fit_artifact_not_a_substrate_boundary) **survives** — the
refutation removes a mislabelled mechanism, not the conclusion.

**Caveats.** Ran **F1 only** — not F2, where the open Theorem-3 sub-claim (*"F2 Sterbenz-region b_k excludes 0"*,
HR31/R4) lives, so **Task A does not close that sub-claim**; it contributes the methodological finding that the
